    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b1e8d9ab-d5fd-4652-8683-7b18d9b6d55a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 57-year-old Czech male who works as a warehouse supervisor in Brno, a physically demanding job that requires him to spend long hours on his feet walking across large storage floors. He is of stocky build, standing 178 cm and weighing 96 kg, giving him a body mass index in the overweight-to-obese range. He presents to the outpatient orthopaedic clinic walking with a noticeable antalgic gait, favouring his right leg. He winces when rising from the waiting-room chair and mentions that climbing stairs at home has become increasingly difficult over the past two years.\n\n{patientName} describes bilateral knee pain that is worse on the right side, characterised as a deep, aching discomfort that intensifies after prolonged standing or physical activity and is partially relieved by rest. Morning stiffness lasting roughly 20–30 minutes is a daily complaint. He also reports occasional crepitus on knee movement and intermittent mild swelling of the right knee, particularly in the evenings after long shifts.\n\nOutside work, {patientName} enjoys recreational football with friends on weekends, a hobby he has pursued since his twenties, though he has had to reduce participation significantly due to knee pain. He is a social person who enjoys evening gatherings at the local pub where he drinks 2–3 beers a few times per week. He is married with two adult children and lives in a two-storey house, which he increasingly struggles to navigate.\n\n{patientName} is a current smoker (approximately 10 cigarettes per day for 30 years) and admits to a sedentary lifestyle outside working hours. He is generally adherent to prescribed medications but expresses frustration at the lack of improvement with over-the-counter analgesics. He is motivated to explore all conservative treatment options before considering surgical intervention."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:afada778-2126-4c1d-9f6d-d1c46053eb04",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of bilateral knee pain for approximately five years, progressively worsening over the last two. He was diagnosed with gonarthrosis of the right knee three years ago on plain radiography at his general practitioner's office. He has no history of inflammatory arthritis or crystal arthropathy. He has a background of overweight/mild obesity (BMI ~30 kg/m²), which contributes to the mechanical load on his knee joints. He underwent arthroscopic debridement of the right knee approximately four years ago due to a meniscal tear sustained during a football match; recovery was partial and symptoms have since progressed. He received intra-articular corticosteroid injections into the right knee on two occasions (2021 and 2022) with transient benefit.\n\n{patientName} has a history of well-controlled hypertension managed by his general practitioner, for which he takes medication regularly. He has no prior hospitalisation other than the arthroscopic knee procedure. He smokes approximately half a pack daily and consumes moderate amounts of alcohol socially. He has no known history of diabetes mellitus, renal impairment, or peptic ulcer disease, though he takes a proton pump inhibitor prophylactically with his NSAID therapy. He has a known allergy to penicillin manifesting as urticaria. There is no history of prior deep vein thrombosis or cardiovascular events."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}